Added from dead card, 2025: 
 Locality: Revilla Gigedo Islands, Socorro Island, Benner's Cove "At lower altitudes, particularly along the lavanear the beaches." Dr. Mason says this is from Clarion Island. A form on Socorro resembles it superficially---ripe fruits are red on some plants and yellow on others. On Socorro there are not as many cacti now as thereewere in 1925, but on Clarion they are more obvious now. On San Benedicto there are no cacti.

notes: 18-X-65, largest stem 26 cm., succulent thruout. Lvs. linear, flattened, 4 cm. long, 3 mm. wide, 2 mm. thick with sparse white hairs from If. bases. Flr. terminal (head) fl. lvs. 7, radiating, otherwise as stem lvs. Calyx 1 cm. long, 7 mm. wide, ovate-acute, margins incurved & hyline. Petals magenta with a basal brown mark ca. 7 mm. long, prxdx Obovate, retuse, 2 mm. long & wide. Filaments blackish-purple, pollen golden yellow, style magenta, 5-lobed. The floral apex is densely white wooly. Stem 3 to 4 mm. thick & erect. Branches are formed from the apex downwards at leaf nodes. This appears to be a new species.
